  "text": "Niche conservation, evolution, and convergence are all seen in Caprifolium. Within North America, there is extensive evolution of the niche. For example, the closely related L. sempervirens and L. albiflora encompass the largest and smallest values for annual precipitation in the group. Likewise, the sister species L. hirsuta and L. ciliosa show dramatic differences in many temperature variables. This was also reflected in the ANOVA, PCA, and niche equivalency analyses that showed differences in every pair of sister species excluding the Asian clade and L. arizonica plus L. dioica. Unfortunately, we had few specimens of L. carnosifolia, which might have affected this comparison. The PCA involving L. arizonica and L. dioica demonstrated that species can be very similar along one niche axis (precipitation), where L. dioica encompasses a wider range in precipitation, but markedly different along another (temperature). These 2 species also occur in widely separated geographic areas: the southwest in the case of L. arizonica, and north central and eastern North America for L. dioica. Only the Asian clade and L. stabiana and L. etrusca were found to be equivalent based on the niche model equivalency tests as measured by the D and I statistics [CITATION_1] . This result could also reflect the small sample size in L. stabiana and L. carnosifolia [CITATION_2] .",
